the context of this study, AI technology innovation represents a strategic
resource that can enhance banks’ ability to streamline operations,
improve risk management, and personalize customer experiences,
thereby contributing to superior financial performance. RBV integrates
seamlessly with the study’s focus on AI technology innovation in
banking. By viewing AI as a strategic resource, RBV aligns with the
argument that effective deployment of AI can lead to competitive ad-
vantages for banks, thereby improving financial performance (Rahman,
2023). The study can analyze how different AI capabilities (e.g., ma-
chine learning for credit risk assessment, and chatbots for customer
service) contribute to enhancing specific aspects of financial perfor-
mance metrics like return on assets (ROA) and return on equity (ROE).
RBV may conflict if the study finds that the adoption of AI technologies
by banks does not result in sustained competitive advantage or superior
financial performance. This conflict could surface if the implementation
of AI is not aligned with strategic objectives or if competitors quickly
replicate AI innovations, diminishing their strategic value over time.
Diffusion of innovation theory (Dol) provides a theoretical frame-
work for examining the adoption and diffusion of AI technology inno-
vation within the banking sector and its subsequent impact on financial
performance (Rogers, Singhal, & Quinlan, 2014). Dol posits that inno-
vation adoption follows a predictable pattern, starting with early
adopters and gradually spreading to the mainstream market. By
applying Dol, this study can analyze the factors influencing the adoption
of AI innovation by banks across different countries, the rate of diffusion
over time, and its implications for financial performance. Dol integrates
with the study by framing AI technology adoption as a process influ-
enced by factors such as technological complexity, organizational
readiness, and market demand. Understanding these adoption dynamics
is crucial for assessing how quickly AI innovations can contribute to
improving financial performance metrics like profitability and efficiency
ratios (Shiyyab et al., 2023). Dol may conflict if the study finds that AI
adoption rates are inconsistent or if certain banks experience barriers to
adopting AI technologies despite their potential benefits. Conflicting
results could occur if cultural or regulatory factors slow down the
diffusion of AI innovations, limiting their impact on financial perfor-
mance outcomes.
Institutional theory offers a theoretical framework to explore how
regulatory, cultural, and institutional factors influence the adoption and
impact of AI technology innovation in the banking sector across
different countries (Scott, 1995). Institutional pressures, such as regu-
latory mandates, industry norms, and societal expectations, shape
banks’ decisions regarding AI adoption and their subsequent financial
performance (Engvall, 2024). By applying Institutional theory, this
study can analyze how institutional factors interact with AI innovation
to influence banks’ financial performance in diverse national contexts.
Institutional theory integrates with the study by highlighting the role of
regulatory frameworks and industry norms in shaping AI adoption
strategies and practices in banking. By understanding these institutional
pressures, the study can analyze how compliance with regulations and
alignment with industry standards influence the effectiveness of AI
implementations on financial metrics. Institutional theory may conflict
if the study finds that regulatory barriers or cultural resistance impede
banks’ ability to adopt AI technologies effectively. Conflicting outcomes
could arise if varying regulatory environments across countries create
uneven playing fields for AI adoption or if societal expectations
discourage banks from fully leveraging AI’s potential benefits.
2.2. Literature review
Several studies have examined various factors contributing to the
financial performance of banks. These factors include non-performing
loans in banks (Takahashi & Vasconcelos, 2024), regulatory capital in
banks (De Bandt, Camara, Maitre, & Pessarossi, 2018), economic growth
(Alam, Rabbani, Tausif, & Abey, 2021), government regulations (B˘ atae,
