Al-Muharrami, 2021). These studies provide a rich context for under-
standing how banking and finance AI technology innovation (BFAITI)
might influence financial outcomes. Takahashi and Vasconcelos (2024)
identified non-performing loans (NPLs) as a critical determinant of
banks’ financial performance. They demonstrated that NPLs negatively
affect return on assets (ROA), thereby reducing overall profitability. This
finding was echoed by (Duong, Tran, Nguyen, & Pham, 2023), who
found that NPLs diminish ROA by 0.075 across 37 Vietnamese banks
from 2005 to 2020 using fixed effect and two-step system generalized
method of moments models. Regulatory capital’s impact on bank prof-
itability is complex. Tran, Lin, and Nguyen (2016) revealed that regu-
latory capital exerts a dual effect: it negatively impacts banks with lower
capital but positively influences those with higher capital. Their study,
spanning U.S. banks from 1996 to 2013, utilized quarterly panel data to
uncover these dynamics. Economic growth has been shown to positively
correlate with bank profitability. Ledhem and Mekidiche (2020),
employing the generalized method of moments, identified a positive
relationship between economic growth and return on equity (ROE) in
Islamic banks across Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei, Turkey, and Saudi
Arabia from 2014 to 2018. Regulatory frameworks can boost or pose
challenges to bank performance. (Nasreen, Gulzar, Afzal, & Farooq,
2024) found a negative correlation between government regulations,
corruption, and bank performance in an analysis of 309 banks across 15
Asian countries from 2010 to 2020. This study highlights the complex-
ities regulatory environments introduce to banking operations. ICT de-
velopment’s role in bank performance is complex and
context-dependent. Aguegboh, Agu, and Nnetu-Okolieuwa (2023)
discovered that while ICT adoption negatively correlates with ROA, it
positively impacts return on earnings and net interest margin across 35
sub-Saharan African countries. This novel finding highlights ICT’s
multifaceted impact on bank performance.
With the increasing integration of artificial intelligence in banking,
recent studies have focused on its socioeconomic, economic, and
financial impacts. Shiyyab et al. (2023) analyzed 15 Jordanian banks
listed on the Amman stock exchange from 2014 to 2021 and found that
AI significantly enhances financial performance, boosting both ROA and
ROE. Similarly, K¨ onigstorfer and Thalmann (2020) reported that AI
reduces losses in lending, enhances payment security, automates
compliance tasks, and refines customer targeting, all of which bolster
overall performance. Ris, Stankovic, and Avramovic (2020) showed that
integrating AI technologies, such as virtual assistants and machine
learning algorithms, improves bank profitability and performance while
reducing dependence on human labor. These technologies also aid in
fraud prevention and facilitate more informed decision-making pro-
cesses. This demonstrates the AI-driven operational enhancements in
banks’ performance. (Umamaheswari & Valarmathi, 2023) emphasized
the role of AI-powered virtual assistants in enhancing profitability,
improving performance, and reducing human resource dependency,
particularly in the banking sector. This shows AI’s virtual assistants and
performance in the banking sector. (Chhaidar, Abdelhedi, & Abdelkafi,
2023) highlighted the positive impact of fintech innovations, including
the Internet of Things, big data, and AI, on bank profitability. Their
study of 23 European banks from 2010 to 2019, using the fully modified
ordinary least squares model, found a significant correlation between
these technologies and enhanced financial performance. According to
Abrokwah-Larbi and Awuku-Larbi (2024), artificial intelligence in
marketing markedly boosts financial outcomes, customer satisfaction,
internal operational efficiency, and developmental progress by
leveraging artificial intelligence in marketing components such as the
Internet of Things (IoT), collaborative decision-making platforms
(CDMP), virtual and augmented reality (VAR), and personalization
techniques. Their research is grounded in an analysis of 225 small and
medium enterprises (SMEs) in Ghana, utilizing the resource-based view
framework. Madhura, Panakaje, Kambali, and Parvin (2024) asserted
that AI technologies hold immense promise for reducing expenses across
