3.1. Methodology
In this section, the investigation outlines the econometric techniques
employed to scrutinize the influence of banking and finance AI in-
novations on the financial performance of banks. Moreover, it explores
the moderating impact of economic expansion and the intermediary role
of information and communication technology advancement, identified
as notable factors affecting bank financial performance. The segment
begins with preliminary examinations, which include assessments for
slope heterogeneity (SH), heteroscedasticity, serial correlation, cross-
sectional interdependence (CSD), and tests for stationarity. Subse-
quently, the analysis advances to assess the impact coefficients using the
feasible generalized least squares methodology.
First, the study employs the CSD test based on the methodology
outlined by Pesaran (2021) to identify any interdependence among
cross-sectional units. In panel data analyses, assessing for CSD before
selecting the optimal estimator has become a conventional practice.
Researchers have employed CSD to determine the appropriate estimator
in their panel analyses over the years (Appiah, Ashraf, Tiwari, Gyamfi, &
Onifade, 2023). Panel studies involving countries with similar trends
have a high likelihood of spillover effects, where events in one nation
influence the economies of others due to growing economic interde-
pendence (Gyamfi, Ozturk, Bein, & Bekun, 2021).
Next, the study utilizes the SH test developed by Pesaran and
Yamagata (2008) to determine whether there are heterogeneous slope
coefficients present in the panel data. The issue of slope heterogeneity,
stemming from diverse economic and demographic structures, is also
pivotal in panel data econometrics. Heterogeneity illustrates that pa-
rameters of interest vary across cross-sectional units. For instance, in this
analysis, assuming uniform slope parameters in panel data comprising
both extensive and limited panels is inappropriate. To prevent erroneous
results from estimations, the assumption of homogeneity must be vali-
dated (Breitung & Das, 2005).
Subsequently, the study conducts a modified heteroscedasticity test
following the approach proposed by Lütkepohl and Burda (1997) to
check for the presence of heteroscedasticity, which refers to the non-
constant variance of the error terms in the regression model. Hetero-
scedasticity can lead to inefficient estimates and affect the validity of
statistical inferences (Papadopoulos, 2024). By applying this test, the
study ensures the reliability and consistency of the estimated co-
efficients. Serial correlation tests based on the method outlined by Born
and Breitung (2016), is used to explore any evidence of these phenom-
ena within the dataset. This test is employed to detect serial correlation,
which occurs when the residuals of a model are correlated across pe-
riods. Serial correlation can indicate model misspecification and lead to
biased standard errors, resulting in misleading statistical inferences.
Conducting this test helps to identify and address any autocorrelation in
the dataset, ensuring robust and accurate model results.
Moving forward, the econometric methodology proceeds with a
panel stationarity test using cross-sectional augmented Dickey-Fuller
(CADF) and cross-sectional Im Pesaran & Shin (CIPS) tests, introduced
by Pesaran (2007) which are second-generation panel stationarity tests
specifically designed to address the issue of CSD. The results of the CSD
assessment will dictate the type of examination to be conducted. If the
variables are not interdependent across sections, the first-generation
stationarity test is utilized. Conversely, if cross-sectional dependence
exists, the second-generation stationarity test is warranted (Appiah,
Karim, Naeem, & Lucey, 2022). The panel stationarity test is to deter-
mine whether the time series data used in the panel dataset are sta-
tionary, meaning their statistical properties such as mean and variance
do not change over time (To, H. K and Chan, 2024). Stationarity is a
crucial assumption in many econometric models, especially when
dealing with panel data, to ensure valid and reliable inference.
Following the assessment of variable stationarity, we employed
