feasible generalized least squares (FGLS) to analyze the impact elastic-
ities of banking and finance AI technological innovation (BFAITI) on
banks’ financial performance. According to Bai, Choi, and Liao (2021),
FGLS assumes that the residuals follow a first-order autoregressive
process AR (1). By explicitly modeling the autoregressive process, FGLS
effectively eliminates residual autocorrelation, resulting in more effi-
cient estimates. This feature is crucial in panel data analysis where ob-
servations across time may exhibit temporal dependencies, ensuring
that the estimates of BFAITI’s effects on financial performance are not
biased due to autocorrelation. Compared to ordinary least squares
(OLS), FGLS provides more efficient and consistent parameter estimates,
especially when the assumptions of homoscedasticity and independence
of errors are violated (Ghaemi & Hosseinlou, 2023). This is particularly
relevant in dynamic settings like banking where the effects of BFAITI
may evolve. Moreover, FGLS is adaptable and capable of accommoda-
ting various forms of error structure, including heteroscedasticity, serial
correlation, and CSD in panel data analysis (Imran et al., 2024). These
capabilities ensure that the model accurately captures the diverse im-
pacts of BFAITI on banks’ financial performance across the studied
economies while handling longitudinal study issues such as hetero-
scedasticity (varying levels of variance across observations) and serial
correlation (correlation between error terms over time). In summary,
FGLS is not only technically robust but also methodologically advanced,
making it an ideal choice for this study to produce accurate, reliable, and
policy-relevant insights into how BFAITI influences banks’ financial
performance across diverse economic contexts. According to Fomby
