3.3.1. Dependent variable
Bank financial performance is measured by bank return on assets
(BROA), expressed as a percentage after tax. ROA is a key metric used to
evaluate a bank’s profitability by indicating how efficiently it utilizes its
assets to generate profits. A higher ROA signifies better financial per-
formance. This variable serves as the primary outcome measure to assess
the impact of AI technology innovation on banks’ financial success
(Haibo & Manu, 2022). Previous studies have employed BROA as a
measure of financial performance (Adu, Abedin, Saa, & Boateng, 2024).
The yearly ROA of banks in the sampled countries is depicted in Fig. 2.
3.3.2. Independent variable
Banking and finance AI technology innovation (BFAITI) measured by
patent applications granted in the field of banking and finance reflects
the level of innovation within the banking and finance sector specifically
related to AI technology. This variable represents the innovative efforts
and investments made by banks in adopting AI technology to enhance
their operations, products, and services (Kaya, Schildbach, AG, &
Schneider, 2019). Fig. 3 shows the sampled countries annually granted
patents in the banking and finance sector. Numerous studies have uti-
lized different proxies to represent AI technology including patents and
keywords for AI-related terms (Shiyyab et al., 2023). This study uses AI
patents specifically granted in the banking and finance sector which
makes it different and novel from previous studies on AI and banks’
performance.
3.3.3. Control variables
Bank non-performing loans to gross loans (BNPL) measures the pro-
portion of non-performing loans relative to total gross loans and helps
control for the risk associated with asset quality in banks’ financial
performance analysis (Galariotis, Kosmidou, Kousenidis, Lazaridou, &
Papapanagiotou, 2021). Zeqiraj, Gurdgiev, Sohag, and Hammoudeh
(2024) used this variable in their studies on bank performance and
economic uncertainty.
Bank regulatory capital to risk-weighted assets (BRC) represents regu-
latory capital adequacy which is essential for ensuring the stability and
solvency of banks. This variable assesses the capital reserves held by
banks to cover potential losses, thus controlling for the impact of capital
strength on financial performance (Athanasoglou, Brissimis, & Delis,
2008). Several researchers have incorporated this variable in their
studies relating to banking and finance (Siddika & Haron, 2020).
Economic growth (GDPG) measured by GDP growth reflects the
overall macroeconomic environment in which banks operate. It serves as
a control variable to account for external economic factors that may
influence banks’ financial performance (Hakimi, Hamdi, & Khemiri,
2023). This variable has been utilized in numerous research to measure
economic growth (Asongu & Biekpe, 2018).
