Conversely, BNPL shows a negative effect on BROA at the 1 % sig-
nificance level, indicating that banks’ non-performing loans reduce
financial performance by− 0.0703. Non-performing loans indicate that a
portion of the bank’s loan portfolio is not generating income, as bor-
rowers are unable to repay their loans. This suggests a deterioration in
asset quality and an increase in credit risk for the bank (Yurttadur,
Celiktas, & Celiktas, 2019). As non-performing loans accumulate, the
bank may need to allocate more resources to provisions for loan losses,
reducing its net income and profitability (Thornton & Di Tommaso,
2021). This, in turn, lowers the return on assets, as assets are not
generating sufficient returns to cover the associated risks and costs. Non-
performing loans can erode a bank’s capital base, as they may need to set
aside more capital to cover potential losses from defaults (Rahaman &
Sur, 2021). This reduces the bank’s capital adequacy ratio, which is a
measure of its ability to absorb losses and maintain financial stability
(Ozili, 2020). A lower capital adequacy ratio may lead to regulatory
penalties or constraints on the bank’s lending activities, constraining its
ability to generate returns on its assets (Buchak, Matvos, Piskorski, &
Seru, 2024). High levels of non-performing loans can signal financial
distress and poor management practices to investors and stakeholders,
leading to a loss of confidence in the bank’s ability to generate profits
and maintain solvency. This can result in a decline in the bank’s stock
price and market valuation, further impacting its financial performance.
This finding aligns seamlessly with previous literature, such as (Duong,
Tran, Nguyen, & Pham, 2023), underscoring the adverse impact of
non-performing loans on financial performance, as evidenced by the
0.075 percentage point reduction in ROA per percentage point increase
in NPLs in Vietnamese banks. This study’s findings further resonate with
the research by Takahashi and Vasconcelos (2024), which also indicates
that NPLs diminish financial performance in the Brazilian banking
sector. The agreement between these studies highlights the critical need
for effective NPL management to enhance bank efficiency and
profitability.
Moreover, the findings indicate that BRC positively influences BROA,
with banks’ regulatory capital enhancing financial performance by
0.0146 at the 5 % significance level. Regulatory capital represents the
buffer or cushion that banks maintain to absorb potential losses from
unexpected events, such as loan defaults or economic downturns. A
higher level of regulatory capital indicates that banks are better equip-
ped to withstand adverse shocks without jeopardizing their solvency
(Saadaoui & Mokdadi, 2023). By maintaining higher regulatory capital
levels, banks can reduce the probability of default and credit losses
associated with their loan portfolios. This, in turn, leads to lower pro-
visioning for loan losses and higher net income, thereby enhancing their
return on assets. This finding is consistent with prior research conducted
by De Bandt et al. (2018), who also identified a positive relationship
between regulatory capital and financial performance in France. Their
findings suggest that voluntary capital, not constrained by regulatory
mandates, is the sole driver of enhanced performance, while regulatory
capital has an insignificant impact on profitability. This integrated
analysis highlights the importance of understanding the different roles
that voluntary and regulatory capital play in shaping bank performance,
highlighting both the agreement with prior research and the novel
insight into the unique contribution of voluntary capital.
Similarly, economic growth is associated with increased banks’
financial performance by 0.0327 at the 1 % significance level, as
depicted in column (1) of Table 5. Economic growth stimulates demand
for loans as businesses seek financing for expansion, investment, and
working capital needs (Wang, Yang, Tang, & Wei, 2024). Similarly, in-
dividuals may borrow more for consumption purposes, such as pur-
chasing homes or vehicles. As loan demand increases, banks can
generate higher interest income from lending activities, thereby
improving their financial performance (Kar & Swain, 2014). Economic
growth creates a favorable environment for investment in various
