capitalize on these opportunities by providing financing for infrastruc-
ture projects, business expansions, and innovation initiatives. By
participating in economic development activities, banks can generate
additional revenue streams and diversify their income sources. Rising
economic prosperity enhances consumer confidence and increases
discretionary spending (Jonkman, Boukes, & Vliegenthart, 2020). This
can lead to higher demand for retail banking products and services, such
as mortgages, credit cards, and wealth management services. Banks can
capitalize on this trend by expanding their customer base and cross-
selling additional products, thereby boosting their financial perfor-
mance. This discovery aligns with the research inquiry conducted by
reinforcing the notion that economic growth enhances banks’ financial
performance. It particularly highlights the positive association between
interest margins, return on assets, and GDP. However, the outcome is
contrary to the results of Robin, Salim, and Bloch (2018) which highlight
a significant negative relationship between GDP growth rate and net
interest margin as a measure of financial performance, indicating a
counterintuitive dynamic where economic expansion might constrain
interest margins. This contradiction suggests that while economic
growth benefits overall financial health, it may exert pressure on banks’
profitability margins through competitive lending practices or regula-
tory effects. Furthermore, government regulations have a negative
impact on BROA at the 1 % significance level, suggesting that such
regulations decrease banks’ financial performance by 0.208 %. Gov-
ernment regulations, such as interest rate caps or restrictions on lending
practices, can influence banks’ interest income and net interest margins
(Ferrari et al., 2018). If regulatory measures limit banks’ ability to adjust
interest rates or engage in profitable lending activities, it can depress
overall profitability and reduce BROA. Regulatory restrictions may limit
the range of products and services that banks can offer, impose con-
straints on risk-taking behavior, or restrict entry into new markets
(Haque, 2019). These limitations can hinder banks’ ability to generate
profits and optimize their asset utilization, leading to a decrease in
BROA. This finding corresponds to the investigation conducted by B˘ atae
et al. (2021), which unveiled that an enhancement in the efficacy of a
bank’s corporate governance framework was observed to detrimentally
impact the financial outcomes of European banks, underscoring a
pivotal external element influencing these dynamics.
