4.4. Lagged effects
Banks’ financial performance is a dynamic and ongoing process that
unfolds over time. When assessing the influence of AI technology
innovation in banking and finance on shifts in bank financial perfor-
mance, it is crucial to account for its lagged effects. The impact of AI
innovations introduced in the banking and finance sector during a
particular year may not be immediately apparent; instead, it might
manifest several years later. Selecting the initial lag as the timeframe for
the lagged effects of AI technology innovation in banking and finance to
manifest could potentially lead to inaccuracies in estimating the effects
of such innovations on changes in bank financial performance. Recog-
nizing the issue of lagged effects associated with AI technology inno-
vation in banking and finance, this study incorporates the strength of AI
technology innovation in banking and finance from the first, second,
third, fourth, and fifth lag periods as independent variables into Eq. (7),
yielding Eq. (11). The regression outcomes are presented in Table 7. The
results presented in Table 7 illustrate the varying impact of banking and
finance AI technology innovations on banks’ financial performance
across different lag periods. Eq. (11) estimation outcomes reveal that the
coefficients in the table signify the influence of BFAITI on banks’
financial performance, considering lag periods ranging from 1 to 5. In
the initial four periods, an upsurge in banking and finance AI technology
innovation corresponds with an improvement in banks’ financial per-
formance, albeit with diminishing effect sizes and significance levels
over time. This suggests that the immediate response to banking and
finance AI technology innovation is an enhancement in banks’ financial
performance. However, from lag 5 onward, there is a transition to a
negative relationship, indicating that prolonged exposure to the costs of
banking and finance AI technology innovation or the erosion of initial
benefits may result in a decline in banks’ financial performance.
Similarly, these coefficients also reflect the impacts of banking and
finance AI technology innovation on banks’ financial performances,
with corresponding increases observed over four lag periods. Although
statistically significant at lags 1 and 2, this increase, ranging from a
0.000898 (lag 1) to a 0.000901 (lag 2) rise in banks’ financial perfor-
mances, is potentially modest. The diminishing effect sizes and signifi-
cance levels observed over time indicate potential diminishing returns to
AI technology innovation in banking and finance. Initially, the adoption
of AI technologies may yield substantial improvements in financial
performance. However, as AI technologies mature and become more
widely adopted across the industry, the competitive advantage gained
from early adoption may diminish, resulting in a leveling off of financial
performance improvements. The transition to a negative relationship
between AI technology innovation and financial performance observed
after a certain lag period suggests that banks may reach a point where
