4.5. Robustness tests
Table 8 below displays the results of the robustness tests conducted
by altering the methodology and substituting the dependent variable. In
this study, the two-step system generalized method of moments (GMM)
technique was employed to evaluate the validity of the baseline model.
This method is particularly suitable for datasets exhibiting cross-
sectional dependence, heterogeneity, and individual time effects, and
it effectively addresses endogeneity issues (Baffour Gyau, Li, & Adu,
2024). The results obtained using this method are consistently reliable.
In column (1), there is a sustained positive association between banking
and finance AI technology innovations and banks’ financial perfor-
mance, indicating that a 1 % increase in banking and finance AI tech-
nology innovation corresponds to a similar increase in banks’ financial
performance. Additionally, to further corroborate the baseline findings,
the dependent variable was replaced. The banks’ financial performance
variable was substituted with banks’ return on equity (BROE), as
depicted in column (2). The results in column (2) demonstrate that, even
with this modification in measurement methodology, the coefficient for
BFAITI remains significantly positive at 10 %, thus ensuring the
continued validity of the results. The analysis presented above indicates
that the empirical findings from the main estimations remain consistent
and reliable.
5. Conclusion, policy recommendations, limitations, and
directions for future research
This study delves into the complex relationship between banking and
finance AI technology innovation and the financial performance of
banks. It analyzes panel data from 20 economies, employing the FGLS
method for primary estimations and the two-step system GMM tech-
nique for conducting robustness checks. This study seeks to explore the
following research questions: Does AI technology innovation enhance
the financial performance of banks? What mechanisms drive this rela-
tionship? Additionally, does AI technology innovation impact banks’
financial performance across different lag periods? The findings show
that banking and finance AI technology innovation has a positive impact
on banks’ return on assets, indicating that increased innovation in
banking and finance AI technology enhances banks financial perfor-
mance. Conversely, non-performing loans have a negative effect on
BROA, emphasizing the detrimental impact of asset quality on banks’
